  "prompt": "Can tax exemption be availed on tax saving FD for the entire tenure of 5 years by investing 1.5 lakhs in the 1st year?",
  "response": "In India, **Tax-Saving Fixed Deposits (FDs)** allow you to claim a tax deduction under **Section 80C** of the Income Tax Act, 1961. However, there are specific rules and limitations that apply. Here's how it works with your example of investing \u20b91.5 lakh in the 1st year:\n\n1. **Tax Deduction**: You can claim a tax deduction of up to \u20b91.5 lakh under Section 80C for the year in which you invest in the tax-saving FD. This means that if you invest \u20b91.5 lakh in the 1st year, you can claim the full deduction for that financial year.\n\n2. **Tenure**: Tax-saving FDs have a lock-in period of **5 years**. You cannot withdraw the funds or break the FD during this period.\n\n3. **Subsequent Years**: The tax exemption is available **only in the year of investment**. You cannot claim a tax deduction in subsequent years, even if the FD continues for 5 years. For example, if you invest \u20b91.5 lakh in the 1st year, you can claim the deduction only for that year and not for the remaining 4 years.\n\n4. **Interest Income**: The **interest earned** on the tax-saving FD is taxable as per your applicable income tax slab. It is not exempt from tax. The bank will deduct TDS (Tax Deducted at Source) on the interest income if it exceeds \u20b940,000 (\u20b950,000 for senior citizens) in a financial year.\n\n### Summary:\n- You can claim a tax deduction of \u20b91.5 lakh under Section 80C in the year you invest in the tax-saving FD.\n- The exemption is not available for the entire 5-year tenure; it is only for the year of investment.\n- Interest earned on the FD is taxable over the 5-year lock-in period.\n\nIf you want to maximize tax savings over 5 years, you could consider investing in other Section 80C instruments (e.g., PPF, ELSS, NSC) or stagger your investments in tax-saving FDs over multiple years. Always consult a tax advisor for personalized advice.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
